**kubectl get pods \-n kube-system** —------\>This command is used to **check the health and status of the Kubernetes control plane components** and other system-critical pods.

A **Pod**:

* Encapsulates **one or more containers** (usually one).

* Shares:

  * **Network**: All containers in a pod share the same IP address and ports.

  * **Storage**: Volumes can be shared among containers in the pod.

* Is managed by Kubernetes as a **single unit**.

Think of a Pod as a wrapper around your application container(s) plus the shared resources they need.

In Kubernetes, we dont create containers, instead we create pod.  
Pod creating ways:

**1.Imperative way**  
**2.Declarative way**  
![][image10]  
Imperative way means **creating a pod using commands.**  
Declarative way is by **creating yaml file.**

| Part | Meaning |
| ----- | ----- |
| `kubectl` | The Kubernetes CLI tool. |
| `run` | Creates and runs a **deployment** (or pod in older versions). |
| `nginx` | The **name** to give your pod or deployment. |
| `--image=nginx` | Specifies the **container image** to use (in this case, `nginx` from Docker Hub). |

It creates a **Pod** (or a **Deployment**, depending on Kubernetes version) that runs a single container based on the `nginx` image.

The container will pull the image from Docker Hub and run the default Nginx web server.
